WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Hi everyone, I'm Freda, and I'm an epidemiologist turned data scientist.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And this means that I've kind of pivoted from conducting research with neurological data

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
to analyzing health research funding data at the Canadian Institutes of Health Research.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
This also means that throughout my career, I've kind of consistently been presenting various types of data findings

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.000
to various types of non-data audiences.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And these audiences have ranged from basic scientists to clinicians or students or patients,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
and now government executives and policy makers.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
And I've learned a lot, and I don't think I need to convince anyone here of how important it is

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:42.000
for us to be able to effectively present about our data.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Without this skill, our data and our findings stop with us and can't move forward to have any further impact.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
So today I want to talk a little bit about how we can improve our data presentations beyond just avoiding pie charts.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
And how many of you have ever gone to a presentation, and you walked away and you were like,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.000
wow, that was such a great topic, but I had such a hard time listening and focusing,

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
and I don't really remember anything.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Hopefully that hasn't happened this week.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
But no matter what, I might argue that you're not the problem,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
because I'm constantly re-inspired by this topic.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Just earlier this year at work, I was assigned to help a team with some of their analytics,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:22.000
which is pretty common.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
So we worked together, we did a lot of analyses,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
and when it came time to present the results to their stakeholders,

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
they asked me if I wanted to join the meeting,

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
just to see and also maybe be there in case there are any data-specific questions.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
And in their meeting, they talked about aims and goals and questions they wanted to answer.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.000
They presented a bunch of results.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
And the speakers were good, and the slides were very nice.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
But even though I was the one who had actually conducted all of the analyses,

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000
I still managed to walk away from that meeting and not really remember anything

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
and not know what their main message was.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
They had all the pieces that were there,

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
but they hadn't been connected or presented in a way that made them stick with me.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
It was kind of like we were walking through this forest of random facts and findings,

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
but there was no signpost or leader to get us to this destination,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.000
or in this case, our main message.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.000
And just like you would never start leading a group on a hike

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
without first knowing where you were going, your destination,

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.000
you should never start working on your data presentations

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.000
without first identifying what your main message is.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Because once you have this message, you can identify what you need

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
in order to lead your audience towards it

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
in a way that gets them to listen and understand and remember what you're saying.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And this is not always easy when you're presenting a lot of numbers

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.000
to non-data audiences.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Your presentation probably has a bunch of different types of data and analyses,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:37.000
maybe some shiny apps.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.000
But if you're not able to identify what your main message is,

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
your audience definitely won't be able to either.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And we're often so excited to show a lot of stuff.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
But we know that our audiences are never going to remember

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
everything we show them.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
And so kind of prioritizing this one thing we can get to stick,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
that's our goal here.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And a lot of speakers this week have done something similar.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
They'll be talking and they'll say,

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
if you're only going to take away one thing from this presentation,

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:01.000
and they'll just go out and say it.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.000
And that's really the idea here.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And unlike this other story where it was about another group,

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
I've also, of course, been guilty of kind of poor communication

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.000
in my presentations.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:13.000
One particularly vivid memory for me was very early in my career

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.000
it was my thesis proposal.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.000
So it was a very important day.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And I was presenting to a very smart and important group.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
And I just got mixed up as to what the goal of my presentation was.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Instead of identifying a message and kind of telling a story,

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
I just wanted to show them everything I'd done.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.000
I wanted to show them all my data and all my analyses

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
and that I'd left no stone unturned.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
And ultimately I wanted to impress them.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.000
And I wanted them to think I was smart.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
And I thought maybe if I provided so much information,

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
they'd be less likely to ask a lot of questions at the end

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.000
because questions are scary.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.000
And as you can imagine, my presentation was just like

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
this busy, incoherent mess.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
And I was trying to include so much information

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
that I talked way too fast.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And this all came together and resulted in a ton of questions

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.000
because I couldn't identify my message.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
They couldn't identify my message.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
They didn't know what my proposal was about.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
I wasn't leading anyone anywhere.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
I was just kind of presenting defensively instead.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Because once we identify what our main message is,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
we can then identify what information we need

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
to lead our audiences towards it

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
and avoid getting lost kind of in this forest.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And unlike that thesis example that I was just saying,

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
you don't want to try and cram in all your data

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
and all your analyses into your presentation just in case.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Because this usually results in our message getting lost.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
And it's not that you're hiding anything from your audience,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
or I hope you're not,

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
but in focusing on what's relevant,

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.000
you're getting your message across,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
and they're always welcome to ask about that extra stuff later.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
Just like your presentation is kind of one big message,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
you should be focusing on kind of one piece of evidence

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.000
and one smaller message at a time

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.000
to keep your presentation clear and concise.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Because sometimes less is more.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
One of the ways I was able to kind of wean myself off this need

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
to overfill and overcomplicate my presentation

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
was to have supplementary slides,

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
sometimes a lot of supplementary slides.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Because often my need to overfill came from

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
either being so excited to show everything,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:04.000
you know, what if they were interested in it,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
or God forbid, what if it came up in the questions

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:07.000
and I wasn't prepared.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.000
So having all the supplementary slides

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
really helped me to focus on my story,

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
knowing that they were there in case I needed them.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Kind of like, you know, your first aid kit in your backpack

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:16.000
when you're hiking.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Good to know it's there, hopefully you won't need it.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.000
Usually you don't.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.000
And once you have your main message,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
and you know the evidence you need to support it,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
you can start incorporating visuals into your presentation.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:28.000
And visuals are our tools.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Sometimes they're figures, sometimes they're images,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:31.000
sometimes they're just text.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
And I'm not going to sit here and be like, you know,

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
this data should be with this kind of figure,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
you should use this plot for this kind of data,

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
because our work and our preferences can dictate that.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
I mean, I was requested to make a pie chart this year.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:43.000
It's fine.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.000
What I more want to focus on is that our visuals

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
are there to support us.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And one of the ways our visuals can help support us

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
is by making sure kind of each of these smaller pieces

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
of evidence and these smaller messages that we're using,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
we're focusing and emphasizing on one at a time.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And one recommendation I had, again,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
early on in my career was this five by five rule.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Some of you might have heard of it,

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
some of you might have not.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.000
But basically it just means no more than five bullet points

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
per slide, no more than five words per bullet point.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:10.000
And I don't like hard rules.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
There are exceptions to everything, including this.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
But I do think that this kind of rule helps to remind us

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
about two important things with regards to our visuals.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And that is, like I mentioned,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
our visuals are there to support us.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
Our visuals are not there to do the heavy lifting.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And you should never be able to send your slide deck

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
to someone and have them understand what it's about

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
without your accompanying presentation.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.000
The second thing is that our visuals should be kept

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:34.000
as simple as possible.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And I don't mean the figures themselves,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:37.000
because sometimes you're not going to be able

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:38.000
to have a simple figure.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.000
You need a complicated one.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
But if you find yourself trying to include a lot of figures

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
on one slide or trying to cram in more and more text,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:45.000
you should probably be breaking this slide up

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.000
into multiple slides.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
One, because you're probably not focusing and emphasizing

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
on one message at a time.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And two, because this just helps our audiences

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.000
with short attention spans pay attention.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
Just like our presentation is kind of

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
one overarching message,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
each slide should have one concluding thought.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
This.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
I remember a visiting scholar one time

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
coming to do a presentation at my old work.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
And he was supposed to give a 20-minute presentation.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
And he went up to the front, and he plugged in his laptop.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.000
And some people noticed that he had something like

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.000
180 slides, and they just panicked.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
But his presentation, his visuals were supportive,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:20.000
and they were simple.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
It's just he had a lot of kind of repetitions

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
where he emphasized different areas or highlighted results,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
and he had a ton of supplementary slides.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
And his presentation was really good.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
Because we shouldn't be afraid of too many slides.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
We should be afraid of really busy slides.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And I think we can all know when we've,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.000
our visuals have become kind of a hindrance

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.000
instead of helpful.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
Because you pull up your slide, and you start talking,

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:41.000
and at some point you look at your audience,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:43.000
and they're peering at your slide,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:44.000
and they're kind of reading it,

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:45.000
and they're trying to understand it,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
and they've completely stopped listening

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.000
to anything you're saying,

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.000
which might be happening right now.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Because you've become secondary to your visual.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And even though figures are often preferred

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.000
over kind of big tables or big blocks of text

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:58.000
to keep your audience's attention,

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
what's more important than the type of visual you use

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
is that you're walking your audience through

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
what it is and what it means.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:06.000
This visual, for example, is fine.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:07.000
This is on our website.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:09.000
You can find it, and it also has the accompanying data

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
that was used to make it.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And the data table has funding type rows

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:14.000
and fiscal year columns,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:15.000
and it's just a bunch of numbers.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:16.000
And the figure is a much clearer way

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
to show these patterns over time.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:19.000
But the second I bring it up,

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.000
I should still be kind of leading audiences

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:22.000
through my presentation.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
I say, you know, here we have figure three, CIHR.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:26.000
Again, that's my work,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Canadian Institutes of Health Research.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
CIHR fiscal year investments by funding type.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And then I kind of dive right in.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:33.000
I say, you know, on the y-axis here

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
we have investments in millions of dollars,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
and on the x-axis we have fiscal years.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And then you go into the data,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.000
and you tell them what the message

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
you want them to take away is.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
It can be as simple as, as you can see here,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:45.000
investigator-initiated research

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:46.000
and research in priority areas

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.000
have been consistently increasing since 2000.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:50.000
This helps the audience

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:51.000
to stay on track with your narrative

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:52.000
instead of just kind of throwing them a compass

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
and trusting that they can find their way.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
It's even better if you can really emphasize

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
the area that you want them to pay attention to.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
If I said something like, you know,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.000
there was a sharp peak,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:02.000
or a sharp rise in research

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.000
in priority area investments in 2020, 2021.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Can anyone guess what the priority area

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
of health research was at this time?

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
If you can replace kind of like a big, busy table

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
with a simple sentence or a figure, that's ideal.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:17.000
But again, what's more important

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:18.000
is that you're leading your audience

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
to your narrative is.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And lots of times I've been presenting

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
to audiences that I thought were very smart,

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.000
I assumed much smarter than I was,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.000
and it made me really shrink away from leading.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
I thought I shouldn't over-explain things

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:31.000
that I might look kind of silly

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
if I was talking down to the audience.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:35.000
But you know your data,

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:36.000
you've done the analyses,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:37.000
and this is your presentation

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.000
that you're supposed to be leading.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Even though it can be really tempting

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:42.000
to assume that any figure you present

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
is so obvious, that the message is so obvious,

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:46.000
they haven't been looking at it

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
for as long as you have.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And no matter what,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:50.000
you should be walking them through it

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
the way I did, kind of axes to data to message.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:54.000
Similarly, if there's a figure

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
you're not gonna walk through,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
don't just throw it on your slide just in case.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
That's when our audiences start doing the peering

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:01.000
and wandering away from us,

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
and that's when our message gets lost.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:05.000
You are there to lead,

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
and your visuals are there to support you.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And finally, you've done your visuals,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:13.000
you can start working on your oral presentation.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.000
And your oral presentation job is

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:15.000
that final step to really get your audience

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
to listen to and understand your message,

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
and hopefully to get that message remembered.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:21.000
And if there's only one thing you can recommend,

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:22.000
or I can recommend,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
about the oral aspect of your presentation,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
it's to say it out loud at least once,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
ideally many, many times.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:29.000
We already spoke about articulation.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:30.000
They really force you to say it out loud

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
before you come here.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:34.000
And as you're making your slides,

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
you're probably already kind of starting crafting

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:37.000
what you're gonna say in your head.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Maybe you're making some slide notes.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
And I know that when I start making slide notes,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
I just tend to write in this weirdly formal way.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:44.000
It's how I write, it's how I email.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
I don't know if it's me or if it was academia.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
But the second I start saying it out loud,

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
I'm able to identify what doesn't actually sound natural

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.000
or feel natural for me,

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
and the areas that I trip over.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And also if I have an area without kind of a main message,

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
I kind of trail off without a concluding thought

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
and it helps me to highlight those.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
They say you shouldn't write a script for your presentation,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:06.000
and I agree,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.000
but the more times you're able to practice

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:08.000
saying it out loud,

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.000
the more natural it'll become,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.000
both in the way you present it,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:11.000
but also if there's little hiccups

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
like technical difficulties or a phone call,

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:15.000
or a random question that comes up.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:20.000
Practicing it out loud is so important.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
Another important aspect of your oral presentation,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
in addition to kind of getting your message across,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.000
is to really create an environment

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
that encourages audience to interact with what you're saying.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
And again, I touched on how questions are terrifying,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:31.000
and I'm often really nervous about them

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
in my data presentations.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.000
But an old supervisor of mine used to say

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
that questions are a compliment,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
and this is because you want your audience

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:39.000
to both have understood,

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:40.000
but also care enough about what you're saying

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
to bother asking a question about it.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And even if they ask those really hard questions,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
that can help maybe identify areas

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
that we've missed before it's too late,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:49.000
or even kind of indicate

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
where we should be heading to next.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
Questions are a good thing.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
And in order for an audience to ask questions,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:56.000
you of course,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:57.000
the most important thing

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:58.000
is that they understood what you're saying.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:11:59.000
But equally,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
providing this kind of encouraging environment

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
where they're comfortable interacting with you

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
is just as important.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:06.000
And that's kind of done in ways

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.000
that we've already touched on,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:08.000
walking through your findings,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.000
language like,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:10.000
see here,

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:11.000
what this is showing,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.000
how to get your message across,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:13.000
versus, you know,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:14.000
obviously this,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:15.000
assuming they can interpret everything,

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:16.000
flipping through slides,

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:17.000
that can make your audience

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.000
a little too lost,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:19.000
or even just too intimidated

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
to ask any questions at the end.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
And this is related to the age-old recommendation

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
of knowing your audience.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:27.000
While you might be comfortable

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:28.000
just providing a bunch of statistical outputs

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
to a group of data analysts,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.000
or scientists,

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:32.000
or whatnot,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
you probably want to provide more context

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:35.000
and more explanation

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:36.000
to a more diverse group

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
of students or stakeholders.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:39.000
Even a posit,

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:40.000
this is my first time here,

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:41.000
I assumed they'd be,

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:42.000
you know,

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:43.000
pretty,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:44.000
we'd all be on the same page,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.000
but once you start talking to people,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
you realize how much diversity there is,

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
even within an audience like this.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So although you should be able

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:51.000
to tailor your presentation

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:52.000
to the audience at hand,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
generally keeping things clearer,

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:55.000
a little bit simpler,

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
just expanding more in your explanations,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:58.000
pausing for your messages,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
that'll really help get your message across,

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:01.000
and encourage your audience

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:02.000
to interact with your findings,

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
which is what we want to invite.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:05.000
Another tiny note

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
about inviting audience interaction,

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
I'm sure everyone's familiar with this,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.000
say you went to a presentation

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
and it's got a lot of results,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:14.000
a lot of different findings,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:15.000
and someone asks a question,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:16.000
they're like,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:17.000
oh, can you go back

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:18.000
to when you were talking about this,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:19.000
and they're like,

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:20.000
no, no, no,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:21.000
like, further, further, further,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:22.000
no, it was before,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:23.000
you know, the slide,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:24.000
the blue dots and the red lines,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:25.000
it can be any presentation,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:26.000
but especially when you have

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.000
really content-heavy presentations,

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
just number your slides.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:30.000
It can help save time

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.000
and just, you know,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:32.000
one little extra step

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:33.000
in inviting that audience interaction

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
we're looking for.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:36.000
And now you've done it.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
You've translated your findings.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
You identified your main message,

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:41.000
you used data

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:42.000
to create a clear path

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:43.000
towards that message,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:44.000
you incorporated

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:45.000
your supporting visuals,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:46.000
and you delivered

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:47.000
an oral presentation

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:48.000
that led your audience

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.000
step by step

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:50.000
through the journey

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:51.000
that you wanted them to take.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:52.000
In keeping your message clear

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:53.000
and understandable,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
you've allowed your findings

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.000
to move beyond you

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.000
and have impacts like,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:58.000
you know,

00:13:58.000 --> 00:13:59.000
inspiring further research

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:00.000
or informing policy

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
or improving business operations.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:03.000
We need to be able

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
to translate our findings

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.000
to a variety of audiences

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:07.000
because in doing this,

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.000
our findings and our data

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.000
doesn't just stop with us.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
It can have further impact.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And in order to do this,

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:13.000
we need to learn

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:14.000
to lead our audience

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.000
towards the message

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.000
and not leave them

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
lost in the data.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:29.000
Thank you, Farida.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:30.000
And as a reminder,

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.000
you can submit questions

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:32.000
via Slido.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
We have a few here.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.000
Do you suggest

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:36.000
different slide decks

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.000
for presenting

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:38.000
versus sharing out?

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:39.000
So if we're presenting

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:40.000
more slides

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:41.000
that tell a story

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:42.000
but condensing

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:43.000
into fewer slides

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:44.000
for sharing out?

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:45.000
Sharing out.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:46.000
Oh, right,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:47.000
like if you are sending it

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.000
to someone

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and not presenting it?

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
No, I still don't think

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
fewer slides is the answer.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:55.000
I still think

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:56.000
when you're sharing

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:57.000
something externally,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:58.000
you will need to write more.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:14:59.000
You're not going to do

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:00.000
the five-by-five rule,

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.000
but I think the main goal

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.000
is to still focus

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:03.000
on that one message

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.000
at a time,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:05.000
and that doesn't mean

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:06.000
you need to condense things.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:07.000
That's the best way

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:08.000
to get your story across,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:09.000
one small message at a time

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:10.000
in order to tell that story.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:11.000
I don't think condensing

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:12.000
really serves us

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:13.000
even when we're sharing out,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.000
except for people

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:15.000
being a little intimidated,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
but that's okay.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:18.000
How do you suggest

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
organizing the supplementary slides

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:21.000
to provide all the extras

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
without the live presentation?

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:24.000
That's a great question,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:25.000
and I think this is really

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:26.000
a preference thing.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:27.000
What I would recommend

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:28.000
that I do

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:29.000
is when I have

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:30.000
my supplementary slides,

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
I have these big title blocks

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:33.000
separating them to sections,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:34.000
so when someone asks

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
about fiscal outcomes,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
say, okay,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:39.000
and I can find

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:40.000
the title slide

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.000
and then look within that section.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
I tend to organize them

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.000
in what I think

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:45.000
is most likely to come up,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
but I think the way

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:48.000
you organize them

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
beyond that is up to you.

